	<h1>
The New Profs on the Block
</h1>
	<div class="page-title-hline">&nbsp;</div>
	










<!-- MAIN CONTENT AREA - START -->



		<div class="floatright">
			<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="sidebar" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_sidebar --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_sidebar --> <!-- InstanceEndEditable -->

<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="Sidebar" --><!-- InstanceEndEditable --><br class="hide" />
			</div>


			<div class="contentcolumn">
				<br class="hide" />
<!-- InstanceBeginEditable name="maincontent" --><!-- FCKEDITOR_maincontent --><!-- /FCKEDITOR_maincontent -->

	<div id="entry-156">
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				
<p>Last summer, the Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science welcomed 5 new professors to the ENCS fold. As the 2009-10 academic year came to a close, the Faculty Quarterly gets to know them a little better while finding out how they're settling in to Concordia. </p>
<p><b><img style="text-align: center; margin: 0px auto 20px; display: block;" class="mt-image-center" alt="Cover_0023.jpg" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/Cover_0023.jpg" height="392" width="440" /></b></p>
<p align="center"><em>From left to right: Hashem Akbari, Andrea Schiffauerova, Govind Gopakumar, Samar Abdi, Shah Jahinuzzaman (photo by Marc Bourcier)</em></p>
<p><strong>Samar Abdi, Assistant Professor in the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering<br /></strong><br />Samar Abdi received his undergraduate education from the prestigious Indian Institute of Technology in his native India. Two years working in industry preceded his decision to pursue a PhD&nbsp; in the emerging field of embedded systems at the Center for Embedded Computer Systems at the University of California, Irvine. Concordia then attracted this approachable young Professor who wanted to be part of a growing university with a strong focus on research. <br /><br />Another draw was the fact that the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering gave Abdi the chance to create a niche for his own research in embedded systems. The design of these systems, which are pervasive computers that are "embedded" into larger electrical, mechanical, biological, or chemical systems, is the main focus of his research. In contrast to a regular computer, embedded systems (which can range from small devices in hearing aids to navigation control systems in aircrafts) must perform application-specific functions and meet several constraints on performance, energy consumption and reliability. Abdi's research focuses on the investigation of novel methods for modeling, synthesizing and verifying embedded systems in order to improve quality and cut cost design.<br /><br />Abdi says his first year at Concordia has been "busy, but incredibly rewarding." Alongside his teaching, he also found time to co-author a well-received book on embedded systems with former colleagues from UC Irvine. As for long-term goals, Abdi hopes to make Concordia the place of choice for research and education in embedded systems. "In my opinion," he explains, "it all starts with developing a world class research program, with a strong emphasis on doing quality work, attracting external funding, and publishing in the most competitive international journals." <br /><br /><b>Hashem Akbari, Professor in the Department of Building, Civil, and Environmental Engineering</b><br /><br />For Hashem Akbari, global warming has been more than just a cause for worry: it has been a call to arms. Before joining Concordia, Akbari spent 26 years at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory at the University of California, Berkeley. As a senior scientist and the leader of the Heat Island Group at the LBNL, he helped initiate research into the environmental effects of what is known as the "urban heat island;" that is, the significant difference in temperature between a city and its rural surroundings, which Akbari's work seeks to mitigate through the use of light reflective roofs, cool pavements, and planting vegetation in urban and suburban areas. This simple idea, says Akbari, can potentially delay the effects of global warming. <br /><br />It was while at Berkeley that Akbari launched an international campaign to develop regional programs to install reflective roofs and pavements in the world's largest cities. Today, he is the coordinator of the "100 Cool Cities" initiative, which works on the idea that investing in energy-efficient green buildings is the opportunity to rebuild communities while recharging the economy. <br /><br />In addition, Akbari has a 5-year-plan to establish a program at Concordia on Customer Demand Response and Building Automation and Integration Controls. Akbari sees enormous potential in Concordia's dedication to innovation of sustainable energy and methods. <br /><br />Reflecting on his first academic year with ENCS, Akbari describes his workload as "very challenging."&nbsp; In between teaching, research, and other departmental activities, Akbari remains in high demand on the lecture circuit and productive on the publishing front. As the author of more than 200 articles, editor of several scientific journals, and active member of several scientific societies, Akbari shows no signs of slowing down as he races to slow down global warming.<br /><br /><b>Govind Gopakumar, Assistant Professor in the General Studies Unit</b><br /><br />Govind Gopakumar is happy to report that his first year at Concordia has been a very productive one--both personally and professionally. In March, he and his wife delightedly welcomed their first child to the world. This marked a major milestone for the couple, who moved to Montreal from California, where both were working. Prior to that, Gopakumar was pursuing his his PhD from the Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute in New York.<br /><br />On the research side of life, Gopakumar has also seen success, having received an FQRSC grant that will allow him to build upon the work he undertook for his PhD dissertation. This research reflects his current academic interest, and the reason the General Studies Unit was eager to have him on board:&nbsp; an academic background in Science, Technology and Society. "My focus has been on urban infrastructure change," says Gopakumar, who aims to "answer questions such as, what governs change and how can one explain change in infrastructure." These timely questions are now set to fuel Gopakumar's research into Public Private Partnerships. This fall, he plans to look into how the infrastructure needs of Canada's First Nations communities are being met and sustained. <br /><br />As for his day-to-day work with the GSU, Gopakumar has found himself fulfilled. In the classroom and in the office, Gopakumar is happily adapting to his new home.&nbsp; When it comes to teaching, he says he has been "extremely happy about the experience." And when it comes to his colleagues, he couldn't be more delighted, noting that "there is a degree of personal association and collegiality that has been a great source of happiness." <br /><br /><b>Shah Jahinuzzaman, Assistant Professor in the Department of Electrical and Computer Engineering</b><br /><br />A career at Concordia seemed a logical step for Shah Jahinuzzaman, who received his PhD from the University of Waterloo in 2009. Originally from Bangladesh, this young professor was attracted by ENCS's large graduate student body, as well as by the Faculty's ties to Montreal's aerospace industry.<br /><br />Jahinuzzaman's research focuses on something that can't be seen by the naked eye: the integrated circuit. These tiny chips consist of millions of transistors that are smaller than the size of an influenza virus. While these nanoscale circuits are less expensive and more powerful than ever before, they suffer from a plethora of design challenges. Their yield and reliability can be particularly affected by the increased imperfections in nanoscale processes, coupled with the incorporation of more and more on-chip functionality. "The goal of my research," Jahinuzzaman explains, "is to develop cost-effective and power-efficient digital circuits that will have the benefits of the nanotechnology without compromising the reliability or yield. While the application of my research ranges from the power-constrained hand-held devices to high-performance microprocessors, I am currently focusing my research on high-speed arithmetic circuits and on low-power embedded memories for biomedical applications." He is currently working towards establishing a world-class circuit research lab at Concordia.<br /><br />Looking back at his first academic year at Concordia, Jahinuzzaman smiles, saying that it was "smoother than what I expected." This positive attitude is evident when Jahinuzzaman speaks of his research progress, praising his graduate students and referring to them as a "bright and highly motivated team." He hopes that the Faculty will keep attracting top-notch graduate students, who, he explains, are "key to establishing ENCS's reputation as research-intensive school."<br /><br /><b>Andrea Schiffauerova, Assistant Professor with the Concordia Institute of Information Systems Engineering</b><br /><br />Andrea Schiffauerova is an expert in understanding and analyzing complex systems. With a research focus on innovation networks in high-tech industries, her specialty is examining how the interaction among the researchers and innovators at universities, companies and labs affects how efficiently discoveries are made and how effectively knowledge is transferred. Despite this comfort with complexity, managing the demands of her first year of teaching in the Faculty of Engineering and Computer Science has been a challenge. "This first year has been very busy; I spent days, nights and weekends just preparing for lectures and getting things in place to initiate my research." With one undergraduate and one graduate course to teach, three grad students to supervise and her own research to pursue, there was little time to explore the many pleasures of Montreal.<br />&nbsp;<br />Fortunately, Schiffauerova is not a newcomer, so settling in to her adopted city has been less of a transition than for some new recruits. Originally from the Czech Republic, Schiffauerova completed her undergraduate studies at home and then indulged her wanderlust by traveling to Jordan to spend a year studying Arabic. She then moved to Canada and completed a Masters and PhD in Industrial Engineering at l'Ã0cole Polytechnique. "I love this city very much, so when Concordia gave me the chance to stay in Montreal I did not hesitate," she says.<br />&nbsp;<br />Schiffauerova, who will begin supervising three new graduate students this fall, sees improving her teaching while making progress in her research as interlinked priorities. She adds that she'd like to help her students move their research towards publication, with the hopes of becoming known nationally and internationally. <br /></p>

